You can implement a custom class ordering in JUnit. 
The configuration option to control the ordering is: 
```
junit.jupiter.testclass.order.default=com.example.demo.CustomClassOrderer
```
Which you can use to provide custom [ClassOrderer](https://junit.org/junit5/docs/5.8.0/api/org.junit.jupiter.api/org/junit/jupiter/api/ClassOrderer.html).


ClassOrderer is responsible for ordering the classes encapsulated in the `ClassOrdererContext.getClassDescriptors()`. 

```
package com.example.demo;

import org.junit.jupiter.api.ClassOrderer;
import org.junit.jupiter.api.ClassOrdererContext;

import java.util.Comparator;

public class CustomClassOrdering implements ClassOrderer {
  @Override
  public void orderClasses(ClassOrdererContext classOrdererContext) {
    classOrdererContext.getClassDescriptors().sort(Comparator.comparingInt(classDescriptor -&gt;
    {
      if (classDescriptor.getTestClass().getName().contains(&quot;A&quot;)) {
        return 0;
      } else return 1;
    }));
  }
}

```

You might need the dependency:
```
&lt;dependency&gt;
  &lt;groupId&gt;org.junit.jupiter&lt;/groupId&gt;
  &lt;artifactId&gt;junit-jupiter-api&lt;/artifactId&gt;
&lt;/dependency&gt;
```
But then you should be able to run the tests normally setting the property, for example: 
```
mvn -Djunit.jupiter.testclass.order.default=com.example.demo.CustomClassOrdering test
```

