There are some dessign patterns that would fit in your business case. A `Factory` for instance to decide which button type to create, or a `Strategy` to decide which behaviour to perform.

But either way, every one needs to take a path or another based on some parameter/attribute/property. You are saying that you want to use the `ID` of the element to do so, that is the same `ID` that would be used as the `PRIMARY KEY` in the ddbb. So meaning two different independent tables, but with a shared uniquenes in the `ID`...

That, as almost everything in software, can be achieved, but it&#39;s a clear code smell, a design smell. Using some id as a discriminator, not for the id value itself, but for the data it represents... Doesn&#39;t make sense.

You can manage to do it, but the solutions you&#39;re gonna use, the workarrounds you&#39;ll have to perform, and the pitfalls that all that would imply will definitely make your code less readable, maintainable and scalable.

A path that would make much more sense is a specific property bound to the buttons that specify the type it is, and use this in the patterns/logic to do/create either one think or another. Efforts towards this solution will give you much better results.

Regarding the database representation of this solution, unless you find a reason why, you don&#39;t even need to have a `TYPE` column, as that can be directly inferred from the TABLE/entity, meaning that it can directly be a constant in the entity.

**Update**

Ok. I think you are mixing here different concerns. The entities should represent data. What is the purpose of having the buttons in the database? They are not data, but presentation. Roles are data, tickets are data, but buttons are not data (unless is a specific type of application in which you build buttons).

I would have a `@Component` for each button type with all the business logic related to that button type.

```java
@Component
public class RoleButtonHandler {

    public doRoleStuff(...) {
        // do roles stuff
    }
   
}
```

```java
@Component
public class TicketButtonHandler {

    public doTicketsStuff(...) {
        // do tickets stuff
    }
   
}
```

Then, instead of an entity, I would just have an enum representing the different button types:

```java
public enum ButtonType {
    ROLE(20),
    TICKET(32);

    private static Map&lt;Integer, ButtonType&gt; ID_VALUES_MAP = Arrays.stream(values()).collect(Collectors.toMap(b -&gt; b.id, b -&gt; b));

    public int id;

    ButtonType(int id) {
        this.id = id;
    }

    public ButtonType getButtonTypeFromId(int id) {
        return ID_VALUES_MAP.get(id);
    }
}
```

And in the event handler, you receive the `id`, you obtain the ButtonType, and based on that you call one component or the other one.

With this approach, even if you want to keep the buttons in the database, which would be in different tables, as you said they have completely different fields, you can easily do that in the dedicated `@Component`, seamlessly.

**Improvement**

I don&#39;t know if this is your case, but if you reveice the ID of the button via json in a rest service, and the ID of the button is decided by you, you can make it a `String`. In that case the `enum` can have only the values, because translating from json to enum that has the same `String` value is automatic, without the boilerplate of translating everything by hand. And the code is more readable.

